### Sequential number

{% sequentialNumberImg /%}

On the top-right or bottom-left corner you can find a number that's not on top of a suit, it is the "Sequential number".

It contains numbers **from 0 to 159**.

Because **each card has a different number**, it is used to reference the cards.

The number has two colors:

- The **black part** indicates the **number of the suit**.  When the _sequential number_ is greater than 120 it no longer indicates the suit number.
  - For example the card 117 has the suit {% suit id=11 /%}, and is the suit number 11 because the black part of the number is 11.
- The **colored part** **matches the color** of the basic suit of that card. It also **matches the rank** of the _basic suit_, and the _3D suit_ (except when the rank is a letter (XJQKA)).

#### Numbers from 0 to 159

Just use the _Sequential number_ as is.

It is used in games that need many unsuited ranks. Games that use it are [The mind](/games/the-mind) and [No thanks!](/games/no-thanks).

#### Numbers from 0 to 59, 2 times

You can also have 2 times numbers from 0 to 59, plus 1 time numbers from 60 to 99, by ignoring the hundreds digit. So, for example, 120 would become 20, and 20 would stay as 20.

#### Numbers from -59 to 100

Similarly, you can also have negative numbers if you treat numbers greater than 100 negative (or positive), to make a distribution of -59...100 (or -100...59).

#### 15 ordered suits of 10 ranks (or vice versa)

You can also make a distribution of 15 ordered suits of 10 ranks (or vice versa) by making the _black part_ the suit, and the _colored part_ the rank.

But it is quite unintuitive to use, so only use this combination if you need ordered suits, or 13 to 15 suits of 9...10 ranks, otherwise it's better to use the ["switched" basic suit](#basic-suit).

### Pyramidal rank

{% pyramidalRankImg /%}

Under the [sequential number](#sequential-number), there's a small number indicating the "Pyramidal rank".

- On the 8 _15-ranked suits_ ({% suit id=0 /%}{% suit id=1 /%}{% suit id=2 /%}{% suit id=3 /%}{% suit id=4 /%}{% suit id=5 /%}{% suit id=6 /%}{% suit id=7 /%}), each suit has: five 1's, four 2's, three 3's, two 4's, and one 5.
- On the 4 _10-ranked suits_ ({% suit id=8 /%}{% suit id=9 /%}{% suit id=10 /%}{% suit id=11 /%}), each suit has: four 1's, three 2's, two 3's, and one 4.

The _pyramidal rank_ has the color of the [basic suit](#basic-suit) in that card.

The _pyramidal rank_ can be used as an alternative rank for games that require an uneven number of specific ranks, like [Hanabi](/games/hanabi).

#### 8 times: five 1s, four 2s, three 3s, two 4s, one 5

Use the _Pyramidal rank_ of the _15-ranked suits_.

There will be left over cards that may be used if the game needs more suits. The unused cards are 4 times: four 1's, three 2's, two 3's, and one 4.

#### 12 times: four 1s, three 2s, two 3s, one 4

Use the _Pyramidal rank_ of the _10-ranked suits_ and _15-ranked suits_, but excluding the 5s.

#### Other pyramidal decks

You can also make pyramidal decks of 10-12 levels without using the _Pyramidal ranks_. Learn how in the [Basic suit section](#basic-suit).

### Coin flip

{% coinFlipImg /%}

Under the sequential number, there's an icon representing "yes" ({% coinFlip id="yes" /%}), "no" ({% coinFlip id="no" /%}) or "unknown" ({% coinFlip id="unknown" /%}). There are 60 {% coinFlip id="yes" /%}, 60 {% coinFlip id="no" /%} and 40 {% coinFlip id="unknown" /%}.

- The 4 first even suits ({% suit id=0 /%}{% suit id=2 /%}{% suit id=4 /%}{% suit id=6 /%}) have a {% coinFlip id="no" /%}.
- The 4 first odd suits ({% suit id=1 /%}{% suit id=3 /%}{% suit id=5 /%}{% suit id=7 /%}) have a {% coinFlip id="yes" /%}.
- The 4 10-ranked suits ({% suit id=8 /%}{% suit id=9 /%}{% suit id=10 /%}{% suit id=11 /%}), have a {% coinFlip id="unknown" /%}.

The coin flip icon has the color of the basic suit in that card.

#### Use cases

It comes in handy when players need to emit a vote and reveal them all at the same time. This voting mechanism can be fond in [The Resistance: Avalon](/games/the-resistance-avalon) and [Secret Hitler](/games/secret-hitler).

Another usage is when there are many copies of 2 to 3 kind of cards. The game [Skulls and Roses](/games/skull) uses this feature where {% coinFlip id="no" /%} are skulls and {% coinFlip id="yes" /%} roses.

### Drawing

Even tough it may seem that by drawing you'll destroy your cards, make them ugly or waste them, the truth is the opposite: **if you don't draw on them, you're wasting the cards**, because they are meant for that. The DIY Multideck provides a solid base to play many games and, additionally, draw in the cards to support more games. Drawing on the cards also make games easier to play, because the drawings can resemble the original game card's.

Rather than filling the cards with predetermined games, I want to encourage you to personalize them by adding the games you enjoy playing. This is why it's called "The DIY Multideck".

{% callout type="info" %}
**Use a pencil** to draw, so you can erase or tweak the drawing if needed. Pens, markers, and other things also work, but I don't recommend using them because making changes is very common.

Anyways, although you can erase the drawings, I generally don't recommend doing it. If you keep the drawings, you won't have to spend time again to prepare that game. It is generally not anoying to play with drawings from other games.
{% /callout %}

When adding new drawings:

- Consider duplicating the drawing on the opposite side slots to make the card playable in any rotation.
- Place them strategically to leave the most usable spots to your favorite games.
- Try to come up with generic drawings that may be used in other games, so you save up space.

In some cases generic drawings can be counter-productive, so be mindfull. For example, consider two unrelated games (A and B) using a similar drawing. On game A, there's a card with a drawing. That same card is also used in game B. But game B is not suposed to have a drawing on that card. So a player can mistakenly think that that card in game B is something special, when it is not.

{% drawingImg /%}

Each card has 14 drawing drawing slots, grouped in 5 drawing areas.

#### {% drawingAreaIcon id="A" /%} Drawing area A

2 rectangular slots on the top and bottom edges.

- The card needs to be hold in hand and contain a big drawing or word.
- The card needs to be stacked on the table while keeping the top or bottom part visible.

#### {% drawingAreaIcon id="B" /%} Drawing area B

4 square slots just below every suit.

- The card needs to be hold in hand.
- The drawing is related to the suit.

#### {% drawingAreaIcon id="C" /%} Drawing area C

6 square slots between the _Drawing areas B_, in groups of 3 columns.

- The card needs a hint, like punctuation.
- The card's hint doesn't need to be visible while holding it on hand, otherwise use the area A.

#### {% drawingAreaIcon id="D" /%} Drawing area D

4 rectangular slots on the center, forming a 2x2 grid.

- The card needs to be placed in the table.
- The card can be hold in hand, but it's the only one.
- The card needs to contain a big drawing or word.
- The card is not used actively during the gameplay, like hints or boards, and your notes cards are full.

#### {% drawingAreaIcon id="E" /%} Drawing area E

1 circular slot on the center, overlapping the _Drawing areas D_.

- You want to represent a tile, chip, token, or similar.
- The card needs to be placed in the table.

### Counting

The back side of the cards also has utility, they serve as counters.

{% callout type="idea" %}
**Optional**: You can add a title to the counter by writing it in the area A of a card and putting it below.

Don't overuse this technique or you'll run out of space, for example, if every player _only_ has to count coins, don't put titles on the counters, it's assumed they are coins.
{% /callout %}

#### Stacking method

{% stackingCounterImg /%}

Count **from 0 to 30** with **less than 10 cards**.

Stack cards upright (worth 1) or upside-down (worth 5), the sum is the result.

The example is counting 13, 3 times 1 plus 2 times 5.

- Cards han be holded in the hand.
- Convinient when coins are exchanged frequently by the players.
- Use when counter needs to be "private" (only known by the own player).

#### Pointing method

{% pointingCounterImg /%}

Count **from 0 to 10** with only **2 cards**.

Put 2 cards on top of each other, and align the arrow from the card in front to point a number in the card on the back, the pointed number is the result.

The example is counting 1, because the arrow is pointing at 1.

- Watch out to not move the cards by mistake or you'll lose the count.
- You can rotate the front card, and count negative or positive points.

It works well as point tracking boards, like the one in the game [Jekyll vs Hyde](/games/jekyll-vs-hyde).

#### Chained pointing method

{% chainedPointingCounterImg /%}

Count **any amount** with very **few cards**.

Create a pointing counter for every digit of the result number.

The example is counting 950, each of the counters is counting 9, 5, and 0, respectivelly, if you concatenate the digits you get the number 950. To create it follow this steps:

1. Take 6 cards (2 for each digit).
2. Create 3 counters side by side (using the [pointing method](#pointing-method)).
3. Move the first pointing card to 9, the second to 5, and the third to 0.
4. The first counter represents the hundreds, the second the tens, and the third the units.

You can also represent decimal numbers with this method, by defining a counter as the decimal point.

## Extra cards

When printing cards on a A3 sized paper, there's room for 18 cards per page. This deck uses 160 cards, leaving 2 blank spaces. This 2 spaces are used in the form of "extra cards", that don't have any suit or rank.

You can use the extra cards in games that need a card with a different background and no information on the front (you can also flip a normal card, but it can be confusing). For example in [The crew](/games/the-crew-1), the "reminder cards".

