## Mapping new games

You may want to play a game that is not on [the official supported games list](/games), so here you have some tips about how to do it.

### Step 1: Finding out the game's components

The first thing you have to figure out is the **components used** on the game, how they are used, and wich can be eliminated. To do so I recommend:

- Find the **official rulebook**, usually there's a section with the game's components.
  - To find it, google the game's name plus "rulebook" or "rules".
  - You can also go to the game's Goard Game Geek entry _Files_ section, usually you find the rules in a PDF.
  - If none of that works, try looking for the rulebook in other languages like german, spanish or french.
- Find **unofficial rulebooks** or other resources explaining the game, there are **websites** dedicated to this.
- Search for **images** of the game.
  - For example on Google Images, Goard Game Geek, or eCommerces selling the game.
- Watch **unboxings or how to play videos** of the game.
- Try to find a **print and play** version of the game.
- Find a fanmade **re-theme** of the game.
  - Usually they are on the game's Goard Game Geek entry _Files_ section.

### Step 2: Map the game

Next, you have to map every component of the game to a feature of The DIY Multideck.

{% callout type="idea" %}
My recommendation is that you go to the [Feature summary](#feature-summary) find out what's the best game system to use.
{% /callout %}

You can also quickly spot the main game system ([Basic](#basic-suit), [3D](#3d-suit), [Sequential](#sequential-number), [Pyramidal](#pyramidal-rank), or [Voting](#coin-flip)) by answering the following questions in order: (There are edge cases not covered)

1. Does it use coins, chips, tokens, progress boards, or similar things? → [Counting](#counting).
1. Does it just use 3 or less types of cards repeated many times? → [Coin flip](#coin-flip).
1. Does it need 1 or 2 cards with a different back face? → [Extra cards](#extra-cards)
1. Does it need icons, words, or extra info on the card (a.k.a. drawings)? → [Drawing](#drawing).
1. Does it have 8 or less suits of 15 or les ranks? → [Basic](#basic-suit).
1. Does it have 12 or less suits of 10 or les ranks? → [Basic](#basic-suit).
1. Does it just have numbers, and are they larger than 30?
    1. Are there numbers larger than 160? → _Not compatible_.
    1. Are there numbers repeated 2 or more times that are larger than 59? → _Not compatible_.
    1. Else → [Sequential number](#sequential-number).
1. Does each rank get repeated?
    1. Is it repeated 4 or more times? → _Not compatible_.
    1. Does it have 7 or more suits? → _Not compatible_.
    1. Else → [3D suit](#3d-suit).
1. Does it have 16 or more different ranks?.
    1. With 6 or more suits? → _Not compatible_.
    1. Else → [3D suit](#3d-suit).
1. Does it use a 3D deck of 5x3x10 or less? → [3D suit](#3d-suit).
1. Does each suit have an uneven distribution where there's just numbers form 1 to 5? → [Pyramidal rank](#pyramidal-rank).
1. Does it have more than 8 suits of more than 10 ranks each?
    1. Does it have more than 16 suits of more than 11 ranks (or vice versa)? → _Not compatible_
    1. Else → [Sequential number](#sequential-number).
1. Else → Probably "_Not compatible_" or "_Low usability_". Read the [deck's manual](/manual) deeper to find the right game system if it exists.

Now you just select the cards the game will need, it will probably be a subset of the game system chosen.

If the game has multiple components, you'll have to put more effort into trying to find a combination of cards that meets all the requirements. To do so, I recommend you pick the main game system used, and use the respective layout on the [Card arrangements](#card-arrangements) section as a visual aid to decide what cards to use for each component.

If the game needs drawings, read the [Drawing](#drawing) section.

### Step 3: Submit the mapping

Finally send us the mapping to [hello@mauriciabad.com](mailto:hello@mauriciabad.com), so we can add it to the website and make it easily accessible to you and other people.

